value.value: The cellular processes that contribute to exocytosis.

label.value: cell-cell adhesion in response to extracellular stimulus

value.value: The attachment of one cell to another cell via adhesion molecules as a result of an extracellular stimulus.
The process by which an organelle membrane interacts with another membrane via molecular tethers that physically bridge the two membranes and attach them to each other.

label.value: catalytic activity, acting on a protein

value.value: Catalytic activity that acts to modify a protein.
Catalytic activity that acts to modify DNA.
Catalytic activity that acts to modify RNA, driven by ATP hydrolysis.

label.value: catalytic activity, acting on a glycoprotein

value.value: Catalysis of a biochemical reaction at physiological temperatures in which one of the substrates is a glycoprotein.

The assembly and secretion a set of components to form an extracellular vesicule, a membrane-bounded vesicle that is released into the extracellular region. Extracellular vesicles include exosomes, microvesicles and apoptotic bodies, based on the mechanism by which they are released from cells and differentiated based on their size and content.
The directed movement of some substance from inside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the extracellular region.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of lymphocyte chemotaxis.
The directed movement of an ammonium ion from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

The series of molecular signals initiated by serotonin binding to a seratonin receptor on the surface of the target cell, followed by the movement of ions through a channel in the receptor complex. Ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

label.value: anterograde axonal transport of neurotransmitter receptor complex

value.value: The directed movement of a neurotransmitter receptor complex along microtubules from the cell body toward the cell periphery in nerve cell axons.
Translation that occurs at the presynapse.

definition.value: Note that this term was created for the SynGO project, and will be obsoleted when the SynGO annotations are made in Noctua.

label.value: translation at presynapse, modulating chemical synaptic transmission

value.value: Translation that occurs at the presynapse, and that modulates chemical synaptic transmission.

definition.value: Note that this term was created for the SynGO project, and will be obsoleted when the SynGO annotations are made in Noctua.

value.value: A vesicle-mediated transport process in which the presynapse take up external materials or membrane constituents by the invagination of a small region of the plasma membrane to form a new membrane-bounded vesicle.

definition.value: Note that this term was created for the SynGO project, and will be obsoleted when the SynGO annotations are made in Noctua.

value.value: A vesicle-mediated transport process in which the postsynapse take up external materials or membrane constituents by the invagination of a small region of the plasma membrane to form a new membrane-bounded vesicle.

value.value: Translation that occurs at the postsynapse.

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein at a synapse.

definition.value: Note that this term was created for the SynGO project, and will be obsoleted when the SynGO annotations are made in Noctua.

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein at a presynapse.

definition.value: Note that this term was created for the SynGO project, and will be obsoleted when the SynGO annotations are made in Noctua.

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein at a postsynapse.

label.value: regulation protein catabolic process at synapse

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein at the synapse.

definition.value: Note that this term was created for the SynGO project, and will be obsoleted when the SynGO annotations are made in Noctua.

label.value: regulation protein catabolic process at presynapse

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein at the presynapse.

label.value: regulation protein catabolic process at postsynapse

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein at the postsynapse.

value.value: A cellular process in which two or more cells combine together, their plasma membrane fusing, producing a single cell. In some cases, nuclei fuse, producing a polyploid cell, while in other cases, nuclei remain separate, producing a syncytium.
The directed movement of hexose from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

Binding to a DNA-binding transcription factor, a protein that interacts with a specific DNA sequence (sometimes referred to as a motif) within the regulatory region of a gene to modulate transcription.
Directly binding to a specific protein and delivering it to a specific cellular location.

definition.value: Examples of protein carriers include the soluble TIM chaperone complexes of S. cerevisiae Tim9-Tim10 and Tim8-Tim13, that provide a shuttle system between TOM and the membrane insertases TIM22 and SAM and, thus, ensure that precursors are kept in a translocation-competent conformation.

value.value: The directed movement of some substance from a cell, into the extracellular region. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via exocytosis.
The directed movement of a lipid from a cell, into the extracellular region.
The directed movement of a lipid from outside of a cell into a cell. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

A stable assembly of two or more macromolecules, i.e. proteins, nucleic acids, carbohydrates or lipids, in which at least one component is a protein and the constituent parts function together in the nucleus.
Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a symbiont that act to protect or prevent damage to the host.
The division of a vacuole within a cell to form two or more separate vacuoles.

label.value: catalytic activity, acting on a nucleic acid

value.value: Catalytic activity that acts to modify a nucleic acid.
The radial migration of a pyramidal neuron along radial glial cells.
The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a non-membrane-bounded organelle.
The elimination of ammonium ions from an excretory cell.
The directed movement of substances from the cytosol into the Golgi apparatus of a cell.
The directed movement of L-phenylalanine from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
Any process carried out at the cellular level that reduces or removes the toxicity of a metal ion.

A homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of a steady state level of a chemical within extracellular body fluids, such as blood, xylem or phloem, of a multicellular organism. This is distinct from maintenance of cellular homeostasis, which occurs within a cell.
A homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of a steady state level of nucleotides within a cell.
A homeostatic process involved in the maintenance of a steady state level of nucleosides within a cell.
The biosynthetic process resulting in the formation of a nucleic acid.

definition.value: This term should not be used for direct annotation. It should be possible to make a more specific annotation to one of the children of this term.

value.value: The cellular DNA metabolic process resulting in the breakdown of a nucleic acid.
